snippet.textDisplay:
I am massively against removing the port for three reasons: Data Transfer, Audio Accessories, and Reliability.


As far as I know, the only way to have lossless transfer of video from an iPhone, or any phone for that matter, is by hardwired connection, e.g. via the port. With my current workflow for projects that I am filming on my phone, this is massively important to keep 100% quality on videos and, to a lesser extent, photos. Most wireless services have some quality loss, and in the case of airdrop, aren't compatible with Windows, or just take forever. For that reason, its really not feasible for me. Additionally, it is nice to be able to plug in a phone and have access to all my pictures and videos on a computer to back them up, saving space on the phone.


Audio when recording has never been the strong suit of phones - most excel in convenience. That's why having the ability to plug a Rode microphone into the lightning (hopefully to be USB-C) port is important - combining convenience with quality. Additionally, most transit agencies don't allow "professional" video on train stations - phones, without tripods, squeak under this regulation. Although I could go buy the new GoPro and get better quality, especially with the shotgun mic attachment that just came out, an iPhone would most definitely be more convenient to carry around than a GoPro.


Also, it's a nice insurance to have the port in case the phone's glass back breaks and ruins the wireless charging coil. Kind of a user error situation, but still nice to have. Additionally, having a hardware interface for trying to recover a bricked iPhone is also a plus.


TLDR; Apple needs to keep the dang port on the iPhone.

snippet.textDisplay: The problem with portless smartphones is that you have to lay them down in order to charge wirelessly and while that isn't really that big of a problem at home it is a big problem in public. Even if the place you were at supported wireless charging (say a train station), just laying your phone flat on a surface like that makes for a prime opportunity for a thief to just snatch your phone and run.

snippet.textDisplay: "the key is to always make things better, and not just change for change's sake" - I hate this philosophy that Apple has. "Better" is so subjective. Genuine creative inspiration is where all the juice is at, even if it isn't technically "better" from a logical standpoint. You can have an artist who is so focused on all the technical aspects of making his paintings as "realistic" as possible but does that mean he is a better artist than someone like Van Gogh or Picasso? Sure his paintings could be realistic looking but they could otherwise be completely dry and lifeless. That is how Apple is feeling to me lately.
